<Document>
<name>Lofoten Islands — E10</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Lofoten Islands — E10</h2><p><i>Norway · Nordland, Fiskebøl to Å (the literal end of the road)</i></p><p><b>150 km of Arctic archipelago — granite peaks falling sheer into the sea, red rorbu cabins, drying cod racks.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>97 km (60 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Full day; ideally 3 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–September (midnight sun late May–mid July); Feb–March for northern lights and dried cod</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Tunnels (some long), sudden weather, sheep, narrow bridges, summer tourist traffic at Reine and Hamnøy</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>151</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Lofoten Wall — a 160 km chain of granite peaks rising abruptly from the Arctic Atlantic — was settled by fishermen drawn to the world's largest cod migration. Stockfish (air-dried cod) has been Norway's main export for 1,000 years; the wooden drying racks (hjeller) along the road from January to April are part of an industry mentioned in 13th-century Hanseatic ledgers. Red-painted rorbu (fishermen's cabins) cluster in every cove. Reine and Hamnøy are the most-photographed villages in Norway — granite spires, red cabins, blue water. The road ends at Å — a single letter, the last village. North of the Arctic Circle (66°33′N) the sun does not set from late May to mid July.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Svolvær</b> — Capital of Lofoten. The Magic Ice bar carved entirely from ice; charter boats out to the sea-eagle nesting cliffs at Trollfjorden.</li><li><b>Henningsvær</b> — Fishing village built on a cluster of rocky islets, connected by causeways. The football pitch (Henningsvær Idrettslag) on a rock surrounded by sea is one of the world's most photographed sports grounds.</li><li><b>Lofotr Viking Museum (near Borg)</b> — Reconstructed 83 m chieftain's longhouse on the site of an 8th-century original — the largest known Viking-era building. Costumed interpreters; Viking ship sailings in summer.</li><li><b>Hamnøy</b> — The view of red rorbu cabins under the granite spire of Festhælltinden is the iconic Lofoten photograph. The bridge at Reine is the standard vantage point.</li><li><b>Reinebringen</b> — 448 m peak above Reine — 1,978 stone steps cut by Sherpas in 2019 lead to the summit. Round trip ~3 hours; the view down onto Reine is one of Europe's great hikes.</li><li><b>Å i Lofoten</b> — Literally just 'Å.' Stockfish Museum and Norwegian Fishing Village Museum are both here. Walk past the museum and you're at the end of the road network — only sea ahead.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
